The map of [Flintshire](/Flintshire), a county in the northeastern corner of [Wales](/Wales), is a visual testament to its historical and geographical nuances. Bordering the English county of [Cheshire](/Cheshire) to the east, and sharing its western frontier with [Denbighshire](/Denbighshire) and its southern edge with [Wrexham County Borough](/Wrexham_County_Borough), Flintshire’s identity is a complex tapestry woven from ancient traditions and modern realities. It carries the name of the [historic county of Flintshire](/Flintshire_(historic)), a designation that now encompasses a different geographical and administrative footprint than its predecessor, hinting at the shifts in governance and identity that time often inscribes upon a landscape. This particular compilation focuses on the enduring markers of [public art](/Public_art) that grace its outdoor spaces, deliberately excluding the more ephemeral or privately held collections found within museums. These are the pieces that speak to the community, standing as silent witnesses to history, commemoration, and artistic expression for all to encounter.

### Bagillt

In the town of [Bagillt](/Bagillt), a solemn [War memorial](/War_memorial) stands as a stark reminder of sacrifices made. Located on the High Street, this monument was erected in 1923. It takes the form of a statue perched atop a pedestal, crafted from [Marble](/Marble), a material chosen for its classic, enduring quality. Its simple yet profound presence speaks volumes about remembrance and the cost of conflict. The details of its creation and specific dedications are noted, but its essence lies in its stoic vigil.

### Buckley

[Buckley](/Buckley,_Flintshire), a town with a strong industrial heritage, also bears the marks of commemoration and civic pride. A [Servicemen and women memorial](/Servicemen_and_women_memorial) was established in 1983–84 under the auspices of the [Royal British Legion](/Royal_British_Legion). This memorial comprises a [Cenotaph](/Cenotaph) and an accompanying sculpture, rendered in a robust combination of [Stone and steel](/Stone_and_steel), reflecting the resilience and strength of the individuals it honors.

Adding a touch of local identity, the [Alyn and Deeside Coat of Arms](/Alyn_and_Deeside_Coat_of_Arms) is also present within [Buckley](/Buckley,_Flintshire). This [Relief](/Relief) artwork, fashioned from [Terracotta](/Terracotta), serves as a visual emblem of the area's historical and administrative ties, a subtle nod to its regional significance.

### Caergwrle

The village of [Caergwrle](/Caergwrle) is marked by its own [War memorial](/War_memorial), situated on Wrexham Road. This monument is a dignified [Celtic cross on stepped base](/Celtic_cross_on_stepped_base), constructed from [Stone](/Stone) and standing approximately 3 meters high. Its design evokes ancient traditions, connecting the sacrifices of the past to a timeless spiritual heritage. The presence of additional images suggests a visual record of this significant landmark.

### Caerwys

In the small city of [Caerwys](/Caerwys), a memorial dedicated to [Arthur Roberts](/Arthur_Roberts) stands as a singular piece. This [Monolith](/Monolith) is carved from [Slate](/Slate), a material indigenous to Wales, grounding the tribute in the very fabric of the land. Its unadorned form allows the material and the subject to speak for themselves, a quiet testament to the individual it remembers.

### Connah's Quay

[Connah's Quay](/Connah's_Quay), a significant town in Flintshire, hosts the [Connah's Quay and Shotton War Memorial](/Connah's_Quay_and_Shotton_War_Memorial). Erected in 1924, this memorial was the work of builder [Edward Jones](/Edward_Jones_(builder)). It takes the form of a [Cross on pedestal](/Cross_on_pedestal), constructed from [Stone](/Stone). This monument holds the [Grade II](/Grade_II) designation, a testament to its architectural and historical importance. Its presence on High Street serves as a prominent focal point for remembrance in the community.

### Ffynnongroyw

The village of [Ffynnongroyw](/Ffynnongroyw) is home to a [War memorial](/War_memorial) located at All Saints Church. This structure, dating from 1994, is a [Pillar with urn](/Pillar_with_urn), crafted from [Granite](/Granite). Its more recent construction, compared to many war memorials, suggests a later commemoration or perhaps a rebuilding or redesign. The use of granite signifies durability and permanence.

### Flint

The county town of [Flint](/Flint,_Wales) boasts several significant public artworks. The [Boer War memorial](/Boer_War_memorial), erected in 1903, is an impressive [Obelisk](/Obelisk) made of [Pink granite](/Pink_granite). Its striking colour and monumental form mark it as a distinct memorial to a specific conflict.

Adjacent to this, another [War memorial](/War_memorial) stands on Chapel Street. Designed by architect [W. B. Edwards](/W._B._Edwards), this [Cenotaph](/Cenotaph) is constructed from [Stone](/Stone), offering a more traditional form of commemoration.

Adding a touch of industrial artistry, the [Railway Station](/Railway_Station) in [Flint](/Flint,_Wales) features a striking [Footplate](/Footplate) sculpture by [Brian Fell](/Brian_Fell). This work, made of [Metal](/Metal), likely references the town's historical connection to railways and industry, transforming a functional space into an artistic statement.

### Hawarden

[Hawarden](/Hawarden), a village with strong historical connections, is home to several notable public artworks and memorials. The [William and Catherine Gladstone fountain](/William_and_Catherine_Gladstone_fountain), located on Glynne Way, was erected in 1889 to commemorate the golden wedding anniversary of William and Catherine Gladstone. Designed by [Edward O. Griffith](/Edward_O._Griffith), it is a [Three-sided fountain](/Three-sided_fountain) made of [Stone](/Stone). This elegant structure, holding [Grade II](/Grade_II) designation, is not just a memorial but a functional piece of civic art.

Within the grounds of [Gladstone's Library](/Gladstone's_Library), a significant stone [Statue](/Statue) depicts [Saint Deiniol](/Saint_Deiniol). Carved by [John Douglas](/John_Douglas_(English_architect)) in 1902, this artwork is designated [Grade I](/Grade_I), signifying its exceptional importance. The saint's presence here connects the intellectual sanctuary of the library with Wales's rich religious history.

A [Second Boer War](/Second_Boer_War) memorial is also situated at [St Deiniol's Church, Hawarden](/St_Deiniol's_Church,_Hawarden). This memorial takes the form of a [Tapering cross on hexagonal base](/Tapering_cross_on_hexagonal_base), constructed from [Stone](/Stone), echoing the ancient crosses found throughout Wales.

In 1920, a prominent [War memorial](/War_memorial) was erected on Gladstone Way, designed by the renowned architect [Giles Gilbert Scott](/Giles_Gilbert_Scott). Standing at 9.1 meters high, this [Obelisk with niche](/Obelisk_with_niche) is made of [Sandstone](/Sandstone). The niche is adorned with a figure of Christ on the Cross, adding a profound religious dimension to the memorial. This significant work holds [Grade II](/Grade_II) status and is a commanding presence in the landscape.

Finally, the grounds of [Gladstone's Library](/Gladstone's_Library) are home to a striking [Statue](/Statue) of [William Ewart Gladstone](/William_Ewart_Gladstone) himself, erected in 1925. Sculpted by [John Hughes](/John_Hughes_(sculptor)), the bronze and stone work depicts the prominent statesman on a pedestal. Originally commissioned in 1910 for Dublin, its presence in Hawarden, Gladstone's home, is deeply significant. This statue is designated [Grade II](/Grade_II).

### Mold

[Mold, Flintshire](/Mold,_Flintshire), the county town, is home to several historically and artistically significant pieces. The [Hallelujah Obelisk](/Hallelujah_Obelisk), located in Rhual near Mold, dates back to 1736. This ancient [Obelisk](/Obelisk) made of [Stone](/Stone) is said to mark the site of a battle from AD 420, connecting the present to a distant and perhaps mythical past.

In the Daniel Owen Precinct, a [Statue](/Statue) of [Daniel Owen](/Daniel_Owen), a celebrated Welsh author, stands testament to his cultural importance. Created in 1896 by sculptor [Goscombe John](/Goscombe_John), this bronze and stone work on a pedestal is designated [Grade II](/Grade_II).

A [War memorial](/War_memorial) graces Bailey Hill in [Mold, Flintshire](/Mold,_Flintshire). Erected in 1926 by [W. B. Edwards](/W._B._Edwards), this [Cenotaph](/Cenotaph) is constructed from [Portland stone](/Portland_stone), a material known for its fine grain and pale color.

Another representation of [Daniel Owen](/Daniel_Owen) is found in [Mold, Flintshire](/Mold,_Flintshire), this time as a stark [Monolith](/Monolith) carved from [Stone](/Stone). Its simpler form contrasts with the detailed statue, offering a different interpretation of the author's legacy.

Lastly, the [Chester Road](/Chester_Road) in [Mold, Flintshire](/Mold,_Flintshire) features a notable [Steam Wheel sculpture](/Steam_Wheel_sculpture). While the artist and specific details are not provided in this entry, its presence suggests a nod to the region's industrial past, transforming a functional element into an artistic statement.

### Rhosesmor

In the village of [Rhosesmor](/Rhosesmor), a [War memorial](/War_memorial) from the 1920s serves as a poignant reminder of those lost in conflict. This memorial is a [Cross on pedestal](/Cross_on_pedestal), fashioned from [Sandstone & limestone](/Sandstone_%26_limestone). It holds the distinction of being [Grade II](/Grade_II) listed, recognizing its architectural and historical significance.

This extensive list, though focused on [Flintshire](/Flintshire), is but a small fragment of the broader landscape of [public art](/Public_art) across the United Kingdom, a testament to the enduring human impulse to create, commemorate, and express through enduring forms. The presence of these works, from solemn war memorials to artistic interpretations of local figures, enriches the public spaces and offers silent narratives to those who encounter them.